Russia has succeeded, in just five years, upholding its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, strong consumers of gas, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us to organically," confirmed François Fillon in inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which major gas contracts are also political and economic.
This explains the broad smiles posted by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number to Lubmin, the destination of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The steel tube submarine is gaine of concrete to protect against ships' anchors.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, to 200 m in length.
For the building, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A 100 had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
It was also necessary to strengthen the measures to protect flora and fauna.
The heavy metal tube is a long snake, as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing stops along its entire length: or valve, or station maintenance.
Control A platform was expected off the coast of Sweden, but the project were abandoned while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Crown corporation Russian settle permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," said Jens Muller.
In case of leakage, the gas content in the pipeline therefore escapes in the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by builders who have planned the welds to hear a flight every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a robot submarine, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a machine that circulates within the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced to the tube, wide of a metre in diameter, and is driven by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 metres second, it provides specific information on any deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without the slightest compensation.
The gas flow is simply provided by the pressure.
It is 200 bars in the departure, and 100 to the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51 percent of the shares.
With are joined the German E. ON and BASF (15.5% each), and the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for a renewable period of twenty years, all of the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the quantity of gas really moved," said Jens Muller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by the shareholders and to 70% of bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are safe to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted pine.
The valves, high of 4.5 metres, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and the characteristics of the gas which may, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
